                    <h2>Grounds for Divorce According to the Turkish Civil Code</h2>
                    <p>
                        Ill-treatment, attempted murder, dishonorable behavior, and adultery are among the reasons that can form the basis for a divorce case. Committing a crime, leading an immoral life without a just cause, leaving the common residence without a valid reason, and having a mental illness are also considered in this context. If the marital union is shaken in a way that prevents cohabitation, a divorce case can be filed. In such cases, a separation request can also be made instead of divorce.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Divorce can be a process that can cause both spouses and children to be affected. Therefore, the divorce lawyer works not only to defend the legal rights of the parties but also to ensure that the spouses reach a resolution without harm.
                    </p>
                    <h2>How Long Does a Divorce Case Take?</h2>
                    <p>
                        Most uncontested divorce cases are concluded at the first hearing. A single session typically lasts about 10-15 minutes. It may take 1-3 months for the decision to become final. The duration of contested divorce cases is longer. The content of the trial, the workload of the court, and the grounds for divorce all affect this duration. The process of contested divorce may last a few months or extend to several years.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If the decision of the family court is appealed to the regional appellate court, the duration of the case will be extended. <strong>Mersin divorce lawyers</strong> manage this process efficiently and accurately, playing a significant role in shortening this period. There is a risk of contested cases without legal assistance taking longer due to simple procedural errors. Moreover, complicated problems that are difficult to remedy may arise.
                    </p>
                    <h3>Where to Apply for a Divorce Case?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Application is made to family courts located in the place of residence of one of the spouses. Alternatively, if there is no family court in the last 6 months where they have resided, the case can be filed in any family court in the region. If there is no family court in the determined location, the case is submitted to the Civil Court of First Instance, which is competent to hear family matters.
                    </p>
                    <h2>Mersin Divorce Lawyer Services</h2>
